<HL>
   British Aerospace Gets Order
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   U.BA AMR
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- British Aerospace PLC's U.S. unit said that
AMR Corp.'s AMR Eagle Inc. regional airline subsidiary has
placed a follow-on order for 35 BAE Jetstream Super 31s, with
options on a further 15 aircraft.
   The total value of the order plus options is about $200
million, British Aerospace Inc. said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The order exercises options for 25 aircraft AMR Eagle had
reserved as part of the Jetstream transaction announced in
June 1989, plus an additional 10 aircraft.
   The airline also has existing options for 50 of the new
Jetstream 41 aircraft, to be operated in a 29-seat
configuration.
   Delivery of the first Jetstream Super 31 from this second
order is scheduled for November with remaining aircraft
delivered by the end of 1991.
   AMR Corp. also is the parent of American Airlines.
</TEXT>
